        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A1 Let f: R2 → R be a function such that f(x, y) + f (y; z) + f (z,x) = 0 for all real numbers x, y, and z. Prove that there exists a function g : R → R such that f(x, y) = g (x) - g(y) for all real numbers x and y.",
        "bbox": [
          0.10131933190835386,
          0.13428082703711777,
          0.4906015024022637,
          0.193313953393295
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Problems_2008_page_001_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(The elements of G in the sequence are not required to be distinct. A subsequence of a sequence is obtained by selecting some of the terms, not necessarily consecutive, without reordering them; for example, 4, 4,2 is a subsequence of 2,4,6,4, 2, but 2,2, 4 is not.)",
        "bbox": [
          0.5545112834608315,
          0.13808139534217018,
          0.919172938756884,
          0.2093253968087292
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Problems_2008_page_001_3",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A2 Alan and Barbara play a game in which they take turns filling entries of an initially empty 2008 × 2008 array. Alan plays first. At each turn, a player chooses a real number and places it in a vacant entry. The game ends when all the entries are filled. Alan wins if the determinant of the resulting matrix is nonzero; Barbara wins if it is zero. Which player has a winning strategy?",
        "bbox": [
          0.10338346628507948,
          0.2048611112106225,
          0.49060150580138645,
          0.30530753978971875
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Problems_2008_page_001_11",
        "observed_type": "list_item",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B1 What is the maximum number of rational points that can lie on a circle in R? whose center is not a rational point? (A rational point is a point both of whose coordinates are rational numbers.)",
        "bbox": [
          0.5338345996776072,
          0.21947674408753579,
          0.921052618788253,
          0.2748015873885964
        ],
        "order": 6
